    "summary": "Recommend \"inherent character\" for running text",
    "content": "**Option 2: \"inherent character (德 De)\"**\n\nBrief reasoning by elimination:\n\n- **\"Virtue\"**: Already argued against -- activates moral frame, shrinks a metaphysical argument to ethics.\n- **\"Defining character\"**: Close, but \"defining\" implies an active agent doing the defining. The author's point is that 德 *appears* inherent (we treat it as what a thing essentially is) even though it is *constructed* from observed regularities. \"Defining\" foregrounds the construction too much; \"inherent\" foregrounds the appearance, which is what the author wants to then deconstruct.\n- **\"Character\"** alone: Too ambiguous in running text. \"The character of a person\" could mean personality, moral character, or a fictional character. Every occurrence would require the reader to disambiguate.\n- **\"Inherent character\"**: Works because it captures the paradox at the heart of the author's argument. 德 is presented as inherent (what makes a thing what it is), but the author shows it is actually constructed bottom-up from phenomena. The word \"inherent\" is precisely what gets deconstructed -- the reader first accepts it, then watches the 道德仁义礼 reversal reveal that this \"inherent\" quality was abstracted from observation all along. The term sets up its own subversion, which is faithful to the text.\n\nIt also works for non-moral entities: \"the inherent character of a dog,\" \"the inherent character of water\" -- natural and clear. Two words in running text is manageable; after a few occurrences, the reader will process \"inherent character\" as a unit."
  }
